      <body>
         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">10/3/87 ¶  ¶ The discovery of Rhododendron, Didymocarpus and Agapetes along with Dracophyllum, Spiraeanthemum, Orites Helmholtzia, Trochocarpa, Helicia, Soramia and Argophyllum on the summit of Mt Bel...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">87.03.10a</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Joseph Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1882-90, ff. 218-219.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Annotated in lead pencil by J. Hooker</seg> And April 21/87 <seg style="font-style: italic; ">[letter not found]</seg>.</p>
               </note>10/3/87</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The discovery of <name key="Rhododendron">Rhododendron</name>, <name key="Didymocarpus">Didymocarpus</name> and <name key="Agapetes">Agapetes</name> along with <name key="Dracophyllum">Dracophyllum</name>, <name key="Spiraeanthemum">Spiraeanthemum</name>, <name key="Orites">Orites</name>
               <name key="Helmholtzia">Helmholtzia</name>, <name key="Trochocarpa">Trochocarpa</name>, Helicia, <name key="Soramia">Soramia</name> and <name key="Argophyllum">Argophyllum</name> on the summit of Mt Bellenden-Ker<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Qld.</p>
               </note> will interest you, dear Sir Joseph; will interest you; it is a strange “mélange” in the Australian flora.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I had some correspondence and a personal interview with Dr Macgillivray concerning your son Brian. It seems, that a vacancy will likely occur at the School of Mines at Bendigo<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Vic.</p>
               </note> in the Directorship, and Dr MacG. is justly eager to secure your sons high ability for the position, if really it becomes open. I have however pointed out to the Doctor, who is the leading spirit on the Committee, — that it must be borne in mind, while your sons present position is one in actual Gov. service, — the Directorship of the Bendigo institution is under local administration, altho’ the school is endowed to some extent by Government. So the question has to be carefully considered. Let me offer my felicitation to the centenary anniversary of the Bot. Magaz. or rather the issue of the 100th vol.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Vol. 113 of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Curtis’s Botanical Magazine </seg>was published in 1887. M apparently assumed that William Hooker took over the editorship at vol. 14, Curtis having died after he had edited vol. 13. Hooker did not commence editing the journal until vol. 54, in 1827, taking over from John Sims who is credited with having edited vols 15–53, although he also edited vol. 14, credited to Curtis on its title page (<seg style="">Hemsley (1906))</seg>.</p>
               </note> Let me hope, that this “magnum opus” will celebrate other centenary jubilees! as a heirloom in your family.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Ever Regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd von Mueller<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The valediction is written in the margin of the final page of f. 218. The following text, on f. 219 which is stamped 'Royal Gardens Kew 2 May 1887, is on similar paper, and is placed here on the basis of the dates of its annotations (see below). The date stamp on the front of the folio is consistent with this sheet having been folded inside the dated folio, so that it would have been the side that was on top when the letter was opened.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">The <name key="Helicia%20Sayeri">Helicia Sayeri</name>, described from flowering specimens only,<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <name key="Helicia%20Sayeri">Helicia Sayeri</name>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">underlined in lead pencil</seg>. Described in B86.11.01, p. 93, <seg style="font-style: italic; ">as H. sayeriana</seg>.</p>
               </note> proves after the discovery of the fruit to be a new genus, to which I have given the name Hollandaea.<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <name key="Hollandaea%20">Hollandaea </name>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">underlined in red pencil</seg>. M erected <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Hollandaea</seg> (<seg style="font-style: italic; ">H. sayeri</seg>) in B87.06.01, p. 173.</p>
               </note> Perhaps, when you happen to meet Sir Henry Holland, you will mention this to the Right Hon. Gentleman. This naming will be regarded as particularly appropriate, because among Austral <name key="Proteaceae">Proteaceae</name> the genera <name key="Buckinghamia">Buckinghamia</name>, <name key="Cardwellia">Cardwellia</name>, <name key="Carnarvonia">Carnarvonia</name>, and <name key="Hicksbeachia">Hicksbeachia</name> were already established<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Buckinghamia">Buckinghamia</name>
                     </seg>, <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Cardwellia">Cardwellia</name>
                     </seg>, <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Carnarvonia">Carnarvonia</name>
                     </seg>, and <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Hicksbeachia">Hicksbeachia</name>
                     </seg> were all erected by M.</p>
               </note> in honor of former Secretaries of State for the Colonies.<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">MS annotations in lead pencil on f. 219</seg>: </p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Kept in [Mus] – JRJ. [<seg style="font-style: italic; ">i.e. J. Jackson</seg>] 18/7/87 [<seg style="font-style: italic; ">at top of sheet, above date stamp </seg>
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Royal Gardens Kew 2 May 1887. <seg style="font-style: italic; ">The remaining annotations are below the stamp, and fill the folio</seg>.]</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Memo of this in [genus] Helecia so that note may be added to Mueller's specimen when it comes to be laid in, D.O. [<seg style="font-style: italic; ">i.e. Daniel Oliver</seg>]</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/> 3 V. 87 | Too large &amp; woody for herbarium JGB [<seg style="font-style: italic; ">i.e. J. Baker</seg>]</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>A note to this effect stuck in cover of <seg style="">
                        <hi rend="underline">Helicia</hi>
                     </seg>. We shd. like the <seg style="">
                        <hi rend="underline">pericarp</hi>
                     </seg> of Mr Watson's fruit. <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>D.O. [<seg style="font-style: italic; ">There is a pencil line linking this note to Oliver's previous note about the memo added to </seg>Helicia.]</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Annotation in red pencil adjacent to Bakers note dated </seg>'3 v 87': Seeds Recd. 11/7 87.</p>
                  <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The annotations apparently refer to two sets of specimens; the fruit received with the letter on 2 May 1887, and the seeds received on 11 July. The Kew Inwards Book contains no record of the pod received on 2 May, but entry 278 for 1887, notes the receipt on 12 July from M, of 'seeds, <name key="Hollandaea%20">Hollandaea </name>Sayeri, Near entrance of the Russell River | Seed pod sent to Museum'.</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The seeds themselves seem to have been transferred to William Watson, the living collection curator responsible for the tropical plant nursery; Oliver appears to have asked for the pericarp of the specimen sent to Watson. There is a seed pod specimen, in two parts, in the Economic Botany collection at Kew: ECB 45009. The donor is listed as Mueller, but there is no collector mentioned; the Entry Book number given in the Economic Botany catalogue as '87.1887' is in error, as it refers to some seeds of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Scutellaria</seg> from Hong Kong.</p>
                  <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
               </note>
            </p>
